      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        CGT and the Partial Main Residence Exemption for Brisbane Sellers Who Rented Out Their Home
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Many Brisbane owners lived in their property for a period, then rented it out before eventually selling. The CGT outcome in that situation is more complex than a straightforward main residence exemption, and the dates matter enormously.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The full main residence exemption is one of the most valuable concessions in Australian tax law. When you sell the home you live in, you generally pay no capital gains tax on the profit. But the exemption only applies in full if the property was your main residence for the entire period you owned it. If you moved out and rented the property at any point, the exemption is reduced proportionally, and the CGT outcome depends on a calculation that most people find genuinely surprising when they first encounter it.</p>

      <p>This article is an overview of how the partial exemption works. It is not tax advice. The interaction between the main residence exemption, the 6-year absence rule, and the 50% CGT discount is complex enough that you should work through the specifics with a tax accountant before making assumptions about your position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The situation this article addresses</h2>
      <p>You bought a property and lived in it as your main residence. At some point you moved out, and the property became a rental. Now you are selling. You cannot claim the full main residence exemption because the property was income-producing for part of your ownership period. How much CGT you pay depends on the proportion of time you were actually living there, and whether the 6-year absence rule reduces or eliminates the taxable portion.</p>

      <p>This situation is common among Brisbane inner-east owners who moved interstate or overseas for work, rented out their property during that period, and have since returned and are now selling. It is also common among sellers who bought as an investment first, moved in later, and are now selling after a mix of tenancy and owner-occupation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the partial exemption is calculated</h2>
      <p>The ATO apportions the CGT exemption based on the number of days the property was your main residence compared to the total number of days you owned it. The calculation produces a taxable fraction of the total capital gain, to which the 50% CGT discount then applies (provided you held the property for more than 12 months).</p>

      <p>As a simplified example: if you owned a property for 10 years, lived in it for 4 years, and rented it out for 6 years, then 60% of the capital gain is potentially taxable. After the 50% CGT discount, 30% of the total gain is included in your assessable income for the year of sale. On a large gain, that is a significant tax bill. The precise calculation depends on your dates, your tax rate, and whether the 6-year absence rule applies.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 6-year absence rule</h2>
      <p>The 6-year rule is the part of the legislation that most sellers do not know about until they start asking questions. Under Section 118-145 of the <em>Income Tax Assessment Act 1997</em>, if you move out of your main residence and rent it out, you can continue to treat it as your main residence for CGT purposes for up to 6 years, provided you do not elect another property as your main residence during that time.</p>

      <p>What this means in practice: if you moved out, rented the property, and returned or sold within 6 years without having nominated another main residence, you may be able to claim the full exemption despite the rental period. The rule resets each time you move back in and the property becomes your main residence again.</p>

      <p>The catch is the condition about not electing another main residence. If you moved interstate and bought another home that you treated as your main residence during that period, the 6-year rule does not apply. You cannot have two main residences simultaneously for CGT purposes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The date your property first became income-producing</h2>
      <p>This date matters more than most sellers realise. When a property transitions from main residence to rental, the CGT cost base resets to the market value of the property on that date. This means the capital gain is measured from the market value at the time of first rental, not from the original purchase price, for the taxable portion of the gain.</p>

      <p>If your Brisbane property was worth $700,000 when you first rented it out, and you sell it for $1,100,000 years later, the taxable portion of the gain is calculated against the $700,000 market value at the date of first rental, not the original purchase price. A market valuation as at the date of first rental is therefore an important document. If you did not get one at the time, a retrospective valuation may still be possible, but it is harder to defend under ATO scrutiny. Talk to your accountant early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Brisbane sellers commonly get wrong</h2>
      <p>The most common assumption is that renting for a short period creates only a small CGT liability. This can be true, but it depends entirely on when the rental occurred relative to growth in the property's value. If you rented your property during the period when Brisbane values grew most sharply, even a relatively short rental period can produce a larger taxable gain than sellers expect. Conversely, if you rented during a flat market and lived in the property during the period of strongest growth, the taxable component may be modest.</p>

      <p>A second common assumption is that the 6-year rule always applies. It does not. Many sellers who owned interstate investment properties, or who bought another home during their absence, find that the rule is unavailable to them. The election is not automatic and not always accessible.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Records to locate before you sell</h2>
      <p>If your ownership history involves any period of rental, gather the following before you engage an agent or solicitor:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>The date you first moved into the property as your main residence</li>
        <li>The date you moved out</li>
        <li>The date the first tenancy started</li>
        <li>Any periods the property was vacant between tenancies or between tenancy and owner-occupation</li>
        <li>A market valuation as at the date of first rental, if available</li>
        <li>Records of any other property you treated as your main residence during the absence period</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Your property manager should have tenancy records. Your original purchase contract and transfer documents will have the acquisition date. If you cannot find a valuation as at the date of first rental, discuss with your accountant whether a retrospective valuation is worth commissioning before you settle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to get advice</h2>
      <p>Before you exchange contracts on your sale, not after. The CGT calculation affects your net proceeds and therefore your decisions about price, timing, and how you structure the sale. If you wait until after exchange to work through the tax position, your ability to plan around the outcome is limited. A tax accountant who works with property investors regularly will be able to give you a reliable estimate of your CGT liability once they have reviewed the dates and relevant market values. That estimate should inform your sale planning, not follow it.</p>

